Economic theory—such as supply and demand, market equilibrium, or efficiency analysis—applies broadly to **any system involving competition**, whether capitalist, socialist, or mixed. While some theories (e.g., Marxist critiques) focus on capitalism, core economic principles (e.g., scarcity, incentives) are universally relevant. Option D is overly restrictive, as economic tools are used even in planned economies (e.g., cost-benefit analysis in socialism).
